    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>LOPEZ TAKES GOLD</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Walter R. Baranger</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Baranger, Walter R</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steven Lopez of US beats Sin Joon Sik of South Korea and wins gold medal in taekwondo at Sydney Olympics; Hadi Saeibonehkohal of Iran defeats Tuncay Caliskan of Austria and wins bronze medal (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Patience and a penalty point helped propel Steven Lopez of Sugarland, Tex., to a taekwondo gold medal last night, 1-0. Lopez faced Sin Joon Sik of South Korea for the gold medal in the 68-kilogram (150-pound) class, after defeating three opponents by a combined 10 points to 1. The 6-foot-2-inch Lopez used a six-inch height advantage to keep Sin backing away and risking penalties for lack of aggression.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Patience and a penalty point helped propel Steven Lopez of Sugarland, Tex., to a taekwondo gold medal last night, 1-0. Lopez faced Sin Joon Sik of South Korea for the gold medal in the 68-kilogram (150-pound) class, after defeating three opponents by a combined 10 points to 1. The 6-foot-2-inch Lopez used a six-inch height advantage to keep Sin backing away and risking penalties for lack of aggression.</p>
        <p>''I knew that sooner or later they were going to give him penalty points,'' Lopez said. When a penalty point was deducted, Lopez said, a further complication developed.</p>
        <p>''I landed a foot kick, but the crowd was too loud,'' Lopez said. With the judges unable to hear the sound of his kicks against Sin's protective gear, the best strategy became patience. Lopez said that he left his chest open to attack, hoping that Sin's right kick would leave an opening for a return blow.</p>
        <p>''It was a trap, and he fell for it,'' Lopez said. With about a minute left in the final round and the match scoreless, Sin tried the kick and Lopez countered to score the winning point.</p>
        <p>Under taekwondo rules, the point total was recorded as 1-1, but the penalty deduction meant a decision for Lopez, 1-0.</p>
        <p>Walter R. Baranger</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000: ROUNDUP -- TAEKWONDO</p>
      </block>
